article.description: Minnesota native Kelly Miller scored a season-high 16 points, and the Phoenix Mercury held off a late rally to beat the Lynx 95-79 on Tuesday night for their third straight victory.
article.headline: Miller scores 16 as Mercury hold off Lynx's late rally
article.linkText: Minnesota native Miller helps Mercury stop Lynx
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS -- It was a frustrating Tuesday night for Nicole
Ohlde and the Minnesota Lynx.

	   Ohlde was 1-for-9 from the floor and the Lynx were beat to
countless loose balls as the Phoenix Mercury raced to a 28-point
lead and hung on to win 95-79 for their third straight victory.
After scoring 19 points and grabbing 13 rebounds in a victory at
Phoenix on June 5, Ohlde couldn't finish around the basket and
combined with her teammates to shoot just 33.8 percent.

	   "You come off a West Coast trip and you're fatigued,"
Minnesota coach Don Zierden said. "I think it showed in our legs,
I think it showed in our shooting."

	   The Mercury, meanwhile, shot 50.7 percent from the floor to hand
the Lynx their worst home loss of the season.

	   Minnesota native Kelly Miller scored a season-high 16 points
while Diana Taurasi returned from a two-game suspension to score 15
points and tied a career high with nine assists for Phoenix. Penny
Taylor, who entered the contest averaging 25.5 points in her last
four games, finished with a game-high 26 points. Tangela Smith
added 12 for the Mercury and Cappie Pondexter had 10.

	   Seimone Augustus led the Lynx with 16 points while Lindsey
Harding added 12, Svetlana Abrosimova scored 11, and Kathrin Ress
chipped in 10. Eshaya Murphy scored all of her nine points in the
fourth quarter as Minnesota fought back from a 28-point deficit
with 7:43 to play to pull within single digits.

	   "They obviously came out with more energy at the beginning --
really the first three quarters," Ohlde said. "We couldn't match
it. You have to hand it to our bench players"

	   After Taylor's 3-pointer gave the Mercury an 84-56 lead, the
Lynx went on a 23-2 run to cut the lead to seven with 2:49 to play.
But Smith, who was traded to Phoenix in the offseason for Harding,
the No. 1 overall selection in the 2007 draft, hit four free throws
and came up with a big steal to seal the victory.

	   Phoenix has won six of its last seven games and four of its last
five on the road. The Mercury won for just the second time in their
last nine trips to Target Center.

	   Before Tuesday's loss, the Lynx had won three straight at Target
Center and four of their last five overall.
